The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                 NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 New Delhi, Jan. 15: An IPS officer, once part of the probes into Rajiv Gandhis assassination and the Kandahar hijack, will head the National Investigating Agency (NIA).          
	The Centre has cleared Radha Vinod Raju, now Jammu and Kashmirs special DGP, as the head of the agency, notified on January 1 to probe federal crimes like terrorism. The cabinet appointments committee chose Raju over IB additional director Nehchal Sandhu and BSF additional DG A.P. Singh.          Sandhu is now tipped to head the Research and Analysis Wing, whose chief Ashok Chaturvedi retires next month.          
	Home minister P. Chidambaram said Raju had been requested to join quickly so he could form the core team of the NIA, compared to the USs FBI.                   
	 Kolhapur (PTI) A third-year medical student has committed suicide in his college hostel allegedly because of exam stress. Suhas Jaganath Patil, 20, hanged himself from the ceiling fan with a nylon rope in his hostel. Patil, from Sakhari in Dhule district, recently appeared in his first-term exam.                   
	 New Delhi (PTI):A government employee cannot be punished for negligence if he writes an official report on a plain piece of paper instead of printed official paper, the Central Administrative Tribunal has held. The tribunal quashed the UPSCs advice of increasing the punishment to a Grade I official.                   
	 New Delhi (PTI): The Indian Coast Guard on Thursday apprehended two Pakistani boats with 17 Pakistanis off the Gujarat coast. The boats were towed off to Jakhau coast where the arrested are being interrogated by the Joint Interrogation Cell. The coast guard was on high alert after the Mumbai attacks.                   
	 New Delhi (PTI): M.N. Prasad, a 1972 batch IAS officer, has been appointed secretary in the Prime Ministers Office. Prasad, a Bihar cadre officer, succeeds Pulok Chatterjee who will join the World Bank as Indias executive director.
                                                                                                                           
